  "prompt": "What are some common myths that are not true?",
  "response": "Here are some common myths that are not true:\n\n1. We only use 10% of our brain (False - we use most of our brain)\n\n2. Lightning never strikes the same place twice (False - it can and does)\n\n3. Cracking your knuckles causes arthritis (False - no scientific evidence supports this)\n\n4. Sugar makes children hyperactive (False - studies show no direct link)\n\n5. Vikings wore horned helmets (False - historical evidence shows they did not)\n\n6. Humans have five senses (False - we actually have more than five)\n\n7. Goldfish have a three-second memory (False - they can actually remember things for months)\n\n8. Napoleon was very short (False - he was average height for his time)\n\n9. The Great Wall of China is visible from space (False - it's not visible to the naked eye from space)\n\n10. You need to wait 24 hours to report a missing person (False - you can report immediately)\n\n11. Vaccines cause autism (False - this claim has been thoroughly debunked by scientific research)\n\n12. Christopher Columbus discovered America (False - Indigenous people were already here, and Norse explorers arrived earlier)\n\nThese are just a few examples of many widespread myths that are actually not true.",
